The largest negative negative correlation (big dark red circle in corrplot) is between Life.Exp and Mat.Mor (-0.857). Also, there is strong negative correlation between: Edu.Exp and Mat.Mor, Edu.Exp and Ado.Birth, Life.Exp and Ado.Birth, and Edu2Fm and Mat.Mor. Strong positive correlation is between Edu.Exp and Life.Exp and Mat.Mor and Ado.Birth.

It is also important to notice that variable GNI has huge variance (min. 581, max. 123124), a lot bigger than other variables.

Principal component analysis (PCA) on the not standardized human data

Now we will perform principal component analysis (PCA) on the not standardized human data.

When we round percetanges of variance captured by each PC, we get that the PC1 holds all the variance (PC1 is 100%). So, basicaly, we get just one dimension. Since the data is not standardized, PCA finds that variable GNI, which has the largest variance, is the most important. Everything else is grouped together, there are no angles between arrows (or arrows whatsoever). The GNI arrow is the longest, because of high standard deviation of GNI.

This graph doesnt tell us anything about the data, execpt the fact that GNI has very large variance in comparison to other variables.

PCA on the standardized human data

Now we will standardize data and then repeat the previous step.

human_std <- scale(human)

# print out summaries of the standardized variables

This time the variance is better distributed along dimensions of principle components. The first one (PC1) shows the max amount of variance between the features (53.6%), the next one (PC2) shows the max variability. So now again we will have a look at biplot that displays the observations by this first two principal components (PC1 coordinate in x-axis, PC2 coordinate in y-axis), along with arrows representing the original variables.

# draw a biplot
biplot(pca_human, cex = c(0.8, 1), col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"), xlab = pc_lab[1], ylab = pc_lab[2])

In the biplot, the angle between the arrows can be interpreted as the correlation between the variables. We can see that for example the angle between Labo.FM and Abo.Birth is almost 90 degrees, which means that there is almost no correlation between the variables (Corr 0.12).

Since arrows of variables Mat.Mor and Ado.Birth are almost parallel, that shows that there is correlation between them. Similary, Life.Exp, GNI and Edu.Exp are also almost parallel so there is strong correlation between them. All of them are almost parralel with PC1 so they are part of this dimension. Similarly, Labo.FM and Parli.F belong to PC2 dimension.

Personal interpretations

To me, the biplot clearly shows relationships between variables and how they group together.

If we look the dimension PC1 we can see two groups of variables. On the one side, we have strongly positivly correlated Maternal mortality ratio and Adolescent birth rate and on the other side there are (also between them strongly correlated): Gross National Income per capita, Life expectancy at birth and Expected years of schooling. Since these two gropus are on oposite sides of PC1, they are strongly negatively correlated.

On the other hand, the dimension PC2 shows positive correlation between Percetange of female representatives in parliament and Ratio of proportion of females/males in the labour force. This group is independant (not correlated) with the groups on PC1.
